<br>
As far as raids go, they are essentially more melee damage which isn't really a bad thing, but that isn't quite all they do. BST can keep the recently modroded and NECs healed while they modulate, do monk-esqe damage when meleeing (with their pet), and although I haven't tried it in very high lvl zones, they have the best petmez in the game. Just like mages they have incredible potential, but it totally depends on the person controling the avatar. If the BST has poor pet control, they yes they are not very helpful, but the same can be said for mage. If guild won't let you bring a pet to raid, there really is no point in you coming at all, and I suggest you work some sense into the raid leader's little noggin.<br>
<br>
Anika, you were pretty harsh in your analysis of BST spells. A BST is a MNK/SHM hybrid (even though Verant has slipped into denial about this, unique class my arse), as far as hybrids go, it seems to me the BST made off like a bandit with spells/abilities. BST has the same healing abilities as RNG when dealing with PCs, SOW, slow, haste, buffs, debuffs, and one badass little pet that makes him a non-stop damage machine. If you have played a 50+ pet class indoors with any regularity, the lack of snare or root doesn't hurt a bit, and a stun line would be vastly overpowering.<br>
<br>
NEC are still the outdoor solo kings as far as I am concerned since the BST would be unable to outdamage his warder pretty much ever. BST is pretty damn near SHM for indoor exp farming, possibly superior for camping named both indoors and out.<br>
<br>
From my experience so far with my two little beasties, 2 BST is by far my favorite duo combination. Contemplating buying another comp and account so I can have 3 and get rid of pet exp penalty all together. Then again, I loved my MAG too until I got to the high lvl game, archaic tactics might very well kill my BSTs too. <p><table><tr><td style="filter:glow(color=gray strength=5);font-family:arial;font-weight: BOLD;font-color:black;font-size:'11pt'">
